<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96722161922223></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96722161922223><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96722161922223>Few things...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96722161922223#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 25th 12:40 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.55]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Keep in mind that the casting time of our charms increases with each additional charm we get. With charm and beguile, you can do a stun, move away, and charm. Higher level ones require you to either root or mesmerize/AE mez one to get it. <br><br>I think that keeping a green or low blue permanently charmed may not be a bad idea, provided you get small pulls. If you get consistently fairly large pulls, why not just charm one of the incoming? It removes a target and still adds the damage you have by keeping a pet from previous fights.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
